 and new pedagogies. Methods for teaching invention using the World Wide Web are also outlined, arguing that the Web allows students and teachers to see into each other's learning processes. In the end, Writing Inventions tells stories—instructional accounts of computers and teaching writing that balance theory and practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEnglish languagexRhetoricxStudy and teachingxData processing. 0aEnglish languagexRhetoricxStudy and teachingxTechnological innovations. 0aEnglish languagexRhetoricxStudy and teaching. 0aHypertext systems. 0aReport writingxStudy and teaching (Higher)xData processing. 0aReport writingxStudy and teaching (Higher)xTechnological innovations. 0aWorld Wide Web. 4aLanguage Arts : Composition and Rhetoric Studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Writing / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978079149031040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791490310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791490310/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles